                            <comment id="17126800" author="azagrebin" created="Fri, 5 Jun 2020 14:11:12 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=chesnay&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;chesnay&quot;&gt;chesnay&lt;/a&gt; which property was configured by the user?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17127603" author="zentol" created="Sun, 7 Jun 2020 11:28:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=azagrebin&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;azagrebin&quot;&gt;azagrebin&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;
[] - Loading configuration property: jobmanager.memory.process.size, 2000m
[] - Loading configuration property: jobmanager.memory.heap.size, 1500m
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17127990" author="azagrebin" created="Mon, 8 Jun 2020 08:03:17 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In this case, we always considered that the overhead is derived as it is not explicitly set. It just turned to have to be fixed as restricted by other option values. We decided to fail fast in case any inconsistencies like this one in user configuration to be explicit about the contracts. The min/max range is a hard contract, only fractions are soft.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We can change a bit the error message to add hints about adjusting min/max or other memory components to pass the check. Then user can at least do this consciously. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17128024" author="zentol" created="Mon, 8 Jun 2020 08:41:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The issue isn&apos;t that it fails, but that it claims something was configured when it wasn&apos;t.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17128303" author="azagrebin" created="Mon, 8 Jun 2020 13:30:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Do you mean that it says that the JVM Overhead was configured? but it says the JVM Overhead was derived. We use `derive` also in user docs.&lt;br/&gt;
The min/max values do not have to be configured, they have default values as well, we could add `configured or default` for min/max.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17128309" author="zentol" created="Mon, 8 Jun 2020 13:41:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&quot;Derived JVM Overhead size (116.000mb (121634816 bytes)) is not in &amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;b&gt;configured&lt;/b&gt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&amp;lt; JVM Overhead range&quot;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17128324" author="azagrebin" created="Mon, 8 Jun 2020 14:06:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, we can add `configured or &lt;b&gt;default&lt;/b&gt; JVM Overhead range`&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17129349" author="azagrebin" created="Tue, 9 Jun 2020 14:31:59 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;merged into master by 9d9ca95c64d9fadf72764dc4f6fbbcbffd5d11da&lt;br/&gt;
merged into 1.11 by 056d677eb27b56751a6a8f4ff74313324265738c&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
